The '''Dnieper River''' ({{IPAc-en|UK|ˈ|d|n|iː|p|ər}},<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/dnieper|title=Dnieper {{!}} Definition of Dnieper in English by Oxford Dictionaries|website=Oxford Dictionaries {{!}} English|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref> {{IPAc-en|US|ˈ|n|iː|p|ər}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/Dnieper|title=Definition of DNIEPER|website=www.merriam-webster.com|language=en|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref>; {{Lang-ru|Днепр|translit=Dnepr}}, {{IPAc-en|ˈ|d|nʲ|ɛ|p|ər}};<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/dnepr|title=Dnepr definition and meaning {{!}} Collins English Dictionary|website=www.collinsdictionary.com|language=en|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref> {{Lang-be|Дняпро/Днепр|translit=Dnyapro/Dnepr}}; {{Lang-uk|Днiпро|translit=Dnipro}}, {{IPAc-en|ˈ|(|d|)|n|iː|p|r|oʊ}};<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/dnipro|title=Dnipro {{!}} Definition of Dnipro in US English by Oxford Dictionaries|website=Oxford Dictionaries {{!}} English|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref>) is one of the major [[rivers of Europe]], rising in the [[Valdai Hills]] near [[Smolensk]], [[Russia]], and flowing through Russia, [[Belarus]] and [[Ukraine]] to the [[Black Sea]]. It is the longest river of Ukraine and Belarus and the fourth-[[List of rivers of Europe#Longest rivers|longest]] river in Europe. 
The total length is approximately {{convert|2200|km|mi|abbr=on}}<ref name=statistics>{{cite web |url = http://landofancestors.com/travel/statistics/geography/237-main-characteristics-of-the-largest-rivers.html |title = Main Geographic Characteristics of the Republic of Belarus. Main characteristics of the largest rivers of Belarus |publisher = Data of the Ministry of Natural Resources and Environmental Protection of the Republic of Belarus. |year = 2011 |website = Land of Ancestors |accessdate= 27 September 2013 }}</ref> with a [[drainage basin]] of {{convert|504000|km²|mi2}}.
The river is noted for its dams and [[hydroelectric station]]s. The Dnieper is an important [[navigable waterway]] for the [[economy of Ukraine]] and is connected via the [[Dnieper–Bug Canal]] to other waterways in Europe.

In antiquity, the river was known to the [[Greeks]] as the [[Borysthenes]] and was part of the [[Amber Road]]. [[Arheimar]], a capital of the [[Goths]], was located on the Dnieper, according to the [[Hervarar saga]].

==Etymology and name in various languages==
[[File:Pontic Olbia Borysthenes.jpg|thumb|250px|Human representation of the Dnepr river (known as [[Borysthenes]]) on an Ancient Greek coin of [[Pontic Olbia]], 4th–3rd century BC]]

The name ''Dnieper'' may be derived either from [[Sarmatian language|Sarmatian]] {{lang|xsc|Dānu apara}} "the river on the far side" or from [[Scythian language|Scythian]] {{lang|xsc|Dānu apr}} (Dānapr) "deep river." By way of contrast, the name [[Dniester]] either derives from "the close river" or from a combination of [[Scythian language|Scythian]] ''Dānu'' (river) and ''Ister'', the [[Thracian language|Thracian]] name for the Dniester.<ref name="Mallory, J.P 2000. p. 106">Mallory, J.P. and Victor H. Mair.  ''The Tarim Mummies: Ancient China and the Mystery of the Earliest Peoples from the West''.  London: Thames and Hudson, 2000. p. 106</ref> <ref>[http://i.ironau.ru/pdf/osjazfolk1949.pdf Абаев В. И. Осетинский язык и фольклор (Ossetian language and folklore). Moscow:  Publishing house of Soviet Academy of Sciences, 1949. p. 236]</ref> Perhaps the name Dnieper (ancient ''Danapris'') is derived from [[Turkic languages|Turkic]] ''Dynporis'' (from Turkic ''tyn'' "quiet" and ''boris'' "winding").<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Будагов |first1=Б. А. |last2=Гейбуллаев |first2=Г. А. |date=1988 |title=Вопросы тюркской этнонимии в трудах М. З. Закиева |url= |journal=Известия Академии наук Азербайджанской ССР. Серия наук о Земле |volume=3 |issue= |pages=128 |doi= |access-date= }}</ref>

In the three countries through which it flows it has essentially the same name, albeit pronounced differently:
* {{lang-ru|Днепр}} ({{lang|ru-Latn|Dnepr}}, {{IPA-ru|dnʲepr|}});
* {{lang-be|Дняпро}} ({{lang|be-Latn|Dnyapro}}, {{IPA-be|dnʲaˈprɔ|}}) or Днепр<ref>Блакітная кніга Беларусі: Энцыклапедыя. — Мінск: Беларуская Энцыклапедыя, 1994. — С. 144. — 415 с. — 10 000 экз.</ref> ({{lang|be-Latn|Dnyepr}}, {{IPA-be|dnʲɛpr|}});
* {{lang-uk|Дніпро}} ({{lang|uk-Latn|Dnipro}}, {{IPA-uk|dnʲiˈprɔ|}}) or Дніпер<ref>[http://hrinchenko.com/slovar/znachenie-slova/12545-dniper.html Словарь української мови / Упор. з дод. влас. матеріалу Б. Грінченко : в 4-х т. — К. : Вид-во Академії наук Української РСР, 1958. Том 1, ст. 394.]</ref> ({{lang|uk-Latn|Dniper}}, {{IPA-uk|ˈdnʲiper|}}).

The late [[Ancient Greece|Greek]] and [[Roman Empire|Roman]] authors called it {{lang|el|Δάναπρις}} - {{lang|el-Latn|Danapris}} and {{lang|la|Danaper}} respectively. Its [[Old East Slavic language|Old East Slavic]] name used at the time of [[Kievan Rus']] was {{lang|sla|Slavuta}} or {{lang|sla|Slavutych}}, the [[Huns]]  called it ''Var'',<ref>Jordanes, ''[[Getica]]'' 269.</ref> and Bulgars - ''Buri-Chai''.{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}} The name in {{lang-crh|Özü}}.<ref>[[:crh:Özü özeni]]</ref> The river is mentioned both by the [[Ancient Greece|Ancient Greek]] historian [[Herodotus]] in the 5th century BC as {{lang|el-Latn|[[Borysthenes]]}} ({{lang|el|Βορυσθένης}}), as well as by [[Strabo]]; this name is [[Scythia]]n (cf. Iranian *{{lang|fa-Latn|varu-stāna}}) and translates as "wide land", referring most likely to the Ukrainian [[steppe]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}} . Unless Icelandic [[Snorri Sturluson|Snorre]] Skald Sturlasson, in [[Ynglinga saga]], meant [[Danube]], which is rather unlikely, wrote that this river run through Great Sviþjoð (Great Sweden), and separate Asia from Europe (also named Enea, from the eponymous [[Aeneas]]). It is, Snorre explains, in his time called Tanais, in earlier times Tanakvisl, and Vanakvisl. This is the realm of the [[Vanir]]. To the east is Asia, and the realm of the [[Æsir]]. In Snorre Sturlasons perspective ancient peoples that were either later deified, or who practiced deification of their rulers, aka [[apotheosis]]. 

==Geography==
[[File:Dnipro estuary.jpg|thumb|satellite image of the Dnieper river estuary, captured 8-Aug 2015]]
The total length of the river is variously given as {{convert|2145|km|mi}}<ref name=statistics /> or {{convert|2201|km|mi|abbr=on}},<ref>Zastavnyi, F.D. ''[http://geoknigi.com/book_view.php?id=798 Physical Geography of Ukraine. Rivers of Ukraine. Dnieper]''. Kiev: "Forum", 2000</ref><ref>Masliak, P., Shyshchenko, P. Geography of Ukraine. Kiev: "Zodiak-eko", 1998</ref><ref>[http://www.dnieper.org/category/50 Website about Dnieper]</ref><ref>Mishyna, Liliana. ''[http://www.hydrography.com.ua/uf/File/Publicat/vd013.009.pdf Hydrographic research of Dnieper river] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304072120/http://www.hydrography.com.ua/uf/File/Publicat/vd013.009.pdf |date=2016-03-04 }}''. Derzhhidrohrafiya.</ref> of which {{convert|485|km|mi|abbr=on}} are within Russia, {{convert|700|km|mi|abbr=on}} are within [[Belarus]],<ref name=statistics /> and {{convert|1095|km|mi|abbr=on}} are within [[Ukraine]]. Its basin covers {{convert|504000|km²|mi2}}, of which {{convert|289000|km²|mi2|abbr=on}} are within Ukraine,<ref name="EoU">{{cite web|url=http://www.encyclopediaofukraine.com/display.asp?AddButton=pages\D\N\DnieperRiver.htm |title=Dnieper River |accessdate=January 19, 2007 |author= |last=Kubiyovych |first=Volodymyr |authorlink=Volodymyr Kubiyovych |author2=Ivan Teslia |work=Encyclopedia of Ukraine  }}</ref> {{convert|118360|km²|mi2|abbr=on}} are within Belarus.<ref name=statistics />

The source of the Dnieper is the sedge bogs (Akseninsky Mokh) of the [[Valdai Hills]] in central Russia, at an elevation of {{convert|220|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name="EoU"/> For {{convert|115|km|mi|abbr=on}} of its length, it serves as the border between Belarus and Ukraine. Its estuary, or [[Liman (landform)|liman]], used to be defended by the strong fortress of [[Ochakiv]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}}

On the Dnepr River to the south of [[Komarin]] urban-type settlement, [[Brahin Raion|Braghin District]], [[Gomel Region]] the southern extreme point of Belarus is situated.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://landofancestors.com/travel/statistics/geography/235-coordinates-of-the-extreme-points-of-the-state-frontier.html |title = Main Geographic Characteristics of the Republic of Belarus. Coordinates of the extreme points of the state frontier |publisher = The Scientific and Production State Republican Unitary Enterprise "National Cadastre Agency" of the State Property Committee of the Republic of Belarus |year = 2011 |website = Land of Ancestors |accessdate= 20 September 2013 }}</ref>

===Tributaries of the Dnieper===
The Dnieper has many [[tributaries]] (up to 32,000) with 89 being rivers of 100+ km.<ref name="splendid">[https://web.archive.org/web/20150704120723/http://www.ukrinform.ua/ukr/news/rozkishniy_dnipro_nemae__rivnoii_yomu_riki_2070837 Splendid Dnieper. There is no straighter river]. [[Ukrinform]]. 4 July 2015</ref> The main ones are, [[orographic sequence|from its source to its mouth]]:
[[File:Muromian-map.png|thumb|right|Dnieper basin showing peoples in the ninth century]]

