[[Category:Geography of the United Kingdom]]
[[Category:Extreme points by country|United Kingdom]]
[[Category:United Kingdom geography-related lists|Extreme points]]

[[Liptako]] is a historic region in [[West Africa]] which included parts of modern-day [[Burkina Faso]], [[Niger]], and [[Mali]]. Control of the area changed hands between several regional ethnic groups, before the [[Gurma people]] established the kingdom of Koala. In the early 19th century, they were in turn overthrown by the [[Fula people|Fula]]. Although a second kingdom of Koala was established to the south of the first, it never reclaimed significant regional power.

The Fula established Liptako as an [[Islamic state]] and an [[emirate]] of the [[Sokoto Caliphate]]. The emir of Liptako was its ruler until the French colonial occupation began in 1897, but retained political power until the position was dissolved by the post-colonial [[Republic of Upper Volta|Upper Volta]] government in 1963. The emir now serves as a [[tribal chief]] on a more local scale.

== Early history ==
Information about the early history of the region that would become Liptako is scant, and no dates or records of rulership are known to exist. The area is believed to have changed hands between various ethnic groups, including the [[Dogon people|Dogon]], the [[Kurumba people|Kurumba]], and possibly also the [[Bambara people|Bambara]], [[Bissa people|Bissa]], and [[Mossi people|Mossi]].{{sfn|Irwin|1981|p=93}}

Beginning in the late 15th century, the region was ruled by the [[Songhai people|Songhai]] as part of [[Songhai Empire|their empire]]. According to the ''[[Tarikh al-Sudan]]'', the first king of the Songhai Empire, [[Sonni Ali]] died during an expedition in the area in 1492.{{sfn|Hunwick|1999|p=100}}{{sfn|Madiéga|1982|p=115}} The chronicle later names Arbinda-Farma Bokar, a son of a daughter of [[Askia Mohammad I]], as having influence in the region in 1549–1550,{{efn|956 AH, according to the [[Islamic calendar]]}} but does not ascribe any particular title to him.{{sfn|Madiéga|1982|p=115}} After the collapse of the Songhai Empire in 1591, the Kurumba probably reestablished control over the region.{{sfn|Madiéga|1982|p=115}}

== Kings of Koala ==
Around 1718, the [[Gurma people]] took control of the area from the Kurumba.{{sfn|Pillet-Schwartz|1999|p=214}} Balibagini, a member of a [[cadet branch]] of the [[List of rulers of the Gurma Mossi state of Nungu|royal family of Nungu]],{{sfn|Irwin|1981|p=94}}{{sfn|Rupley|Bangali|Diamitani|2013|p=112}} established the first kingdom of Koala,{{sfn|Madiéga|1982|p=115}} taking the title ''bedo'' (pl. ''bediba'').{{sfn|Pillet-Schwartz|1999|p=214}}{{sfn|Madiéga|1982|p=255}} The community that served as the capital, also named Koala, was not the present-day town of [[Koala, Burkina Faso|that name]], but a now-lost settlement in the west of the Liptako region.{{sfn|Irwin|1981|p=94}} In establishing his kingdom, Balibagini warred with the Kurumba, pushing them west toward [[Aribinda]], and with the Fula, who were forbidden from the new kingdom. When his brother, Udan Jari, died, Balibagini annexed the territory he had controlled as well. The territory he carved out was larger than later Liptako, stretching as far east as the [[Niger River]].{{sfn|Pillet-Schwartz|1999|pp=214–215}}

Paamba, the fifth ''bedo'',{{sfn|Madiéga|1982|p=123}} lifted Balibagini's edict prohibiting a Fula presence in Koala, setting the stage for the kingdom's eventual fall.{{sfn|Pillet-Schwartz|1999|p=215}} During the reign of the eighth king, Yencaari, a dispute over inheritance and taxation in the Fula village of Selbo escalated a rebellion that ultimately forced the Gurma to flee to the south.{{sfn|Pillet-Schwartz|1999|p=215}} Yencaari was killed during the conflict,{{sfn|Irwin|1981|p=94}} with one local account suggesting that he was injured in battle, succumbing to his wounds in [[Bani, Burkina Faso|Bani]] after the Gurma exodus.{{sfn|Irwin|1981|p=92}} Yencaari's son and heir-apparent, Umaru, was also either killed or disgraced in battle,{{sfn|Pillet-Schwartz|1999|p=215}} although he may have led the Gurma south after their defeat.{{sfn|Irwin|1981|p=94}}

