== Emirs of Liptako ==
Some members of the traditionally [[pastoralism|pastoral]] Fula people began to settle in the Liptako area as early as the 15th century.{{sfn|Irwin|1981|pp=98–99}} In the early 19th century, escalating tensions between the [[Islamization|Islamized]] Fula and the ruling Gurma led to a [[jihad]], inspired by [[Usman dan Fodio]] and the [[Fulani War]].{{sfn|Irwin|1981|pp=90–93}} This conflict destroyed Koala, largely pushed the Gurma out of the region, and established Fula rule.{{sfn|Rupley|Bangali|Diamitani|2013|p=112}}{{sfn|Irwin|1981|pp=90–93}} The newly-established Liptako was not fully independent, but rather an [[emirate]] of the [[Sokoto Caliphate]], administered through an intermediate [[suzerainty|suzerain]] in [[Gwandu]]. Nevertheless, distance and local sentiment permitted Liptako's emir considerable local control.{{sfn|Irwin|1981|pp=123–124,134}} The emirship was a hereditary office with a traditional [[order of succession]] defined by custom. The right of succession belonged to a male-descent child of the earliest surviving [[familial generation]]; within a generation, children of older brothers had precedence over the children of younger brothers, and older brothers were preferred over their younger siblings. However, not all successions passed strictly in this manner.{{sfn|Irwin|1981|p=152}}

The French occupied the Liptako capital of [[Dori, Burkina Faso|Dori]] on 30 April 1897,{{sfn|Irwin|1981|p=73}} during the reign of Bokari Sori, but did not remove the emir, and largely permitted the precolonial political system to continue.{{sfn|Irwin|1981|p=178}} In 1963, [[Maurice Yaméogo]], the first president of the independent [[Republic of Upper Volta]], formally disbanded the emirate.{{sfn|Pillet-Schwartz|2003|p=898}} Nassourou continued to use the title, which remained a source of significant local respect and political influence.{{sfn|Lund|2001|p=42}} Currently, the emir of Liptako serves as a [[tribal chief]] for the Fula in [[Séno Province]].<ref name=Dembele/>

{| class="wikitable"
|- align=center 
! No. !! Emir{{efn|name=fn-names|Fula names prior to 1960 are a series of [[patronymics]], as in [[Arabic names]].{{sfn|Irwin|1981|p=175}} In the post-colonial era, the family of the emirs adopted Dicko as a [[surname]]. Burkinabé sources are not consistent about whether this should appear before or after the given name;<ref name=Dembele/><ref name=Ilboudo/> in this article, this family name is always placed last. The orthography of the [[Fula language]] using the [[Latin script]] was not standardized until 1966,<ref name=UNESCO/> so the spelling of Liptako emirs prior to Nassourou Abdoulaye Dicko varies widely; for consistency, this article spells the names of rulers before 1966 in the forms used by Paul Irwin in his 1981 Liptako monograph. The names of rulers after 1966 are spelled as provided by Burkinabé media.}} !! Rule began{{efn|name=fn-year|Dates consisting of two years separated with a slash are based on the Fula calendar, a [[solar calendar]] that begins approximately in July, based on the start of the rainy season.{{sfn|Irwin|1981|p=73}}}} !! Rule ended !! Notes || Ref(s)
