{{Infobox philosopher |honorific_prefix= |name=Rob Shields |honorific_suffix= |image= |image_size= |alt= |caption= |other_names= |birth_name=<!-- only use if different from name --> |birth_date={{birth date and age|df=yes|1961|06|09}} |birth_place=[[Toronto]], [[Ontario]] |death_date=<!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|1961|06|09}} (death date then birth date) --> |death_place= |residence= |nationality=Canadian |religion= |alma_mater=Sussex University |notable_works=Places on the Margin<!-- use "notable_works" in place of "books" parameter (deprecated) --> |awards=[[Commonwealth Scholar]]; [[Henry Marshall Tory]] Chair; Canadian [http://pagse.org/ Partnership Group in Science and Education] "Leader of the Future" Award 2004 |institutions=[[University of Alberta]] |main_interests=Social theory,cities as social spaces |notable_ideas=Social spatialisation, cultural topology, virtuality |influences=Lefebvre, Henri; Maffesoli, Michel; Podgorecki, Adam; King, Anthony; Preziosi, Donald |website=<!-- {{URL|https://www.ualberta.ca/~rshields}} --> }}
'''Robert MacArthur Shields''' (born 9 June 1961 in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]]) is a Canadian [[sociologist]] and [[cultural theorist]]. He is Professor and [[Henry Marshall Tory]] Endowed Research Chair at [[University of Alberta]]. Shields directs the [https://crsc.ualberta.ca City Region Studies Centre] in the Faculty of [https://www.ualberta.ca/Extension Extension]. From 1991-2004 he rose to Professor of Sociology and Directed the Institute for Interdisciplinary Studies at [[Carleton University]], [[Ottawa]] Canada, with an interlude in 1995-97 as a Lecturer in Culture and Communications at [[Lancaster University]], [[Lancaster, Lancashire|Lancaster]] UK.
Education: Architecture (B.A. Directed Interdisciplinary Studies, [[Carleton University]], [[Ottawa]] [[Canada]]), Sociology (M.A. [[Carleton University]]) and Urban and Regional Studies (D.Phil, [[University of Sussex]]).
==Contributions and notable impacts== 1. Journal founder, [[Space and Culture|''Space and Culture: International journal of social spaces'']] (1997--). ''Curb'' Canadian Planning Magazine (2009-2016). 2. Shields'<ref>{{cite book|title=Places on the Margin|last=Shields|first=Rob|publisher=Routledge Chapman Hall|year=1991|isbn=0-415-08022-3|location=London, U.K.|pages=}}</ref> won a Library Choice 'Book of the Year' award for demonstrating a theory of [[Spatialization|Social Spatialisations]]. Shields argued that geographical places were understood through a network of contrasting places. Social spatialisation influences social action through embodied habit and casting locations as "places for this and places for that". This had significant impact on human geographical definitions of spatiality and understanding of the social and political aspects of geographical space.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bailey|first1=Anne|title=Thinking Space|journal=Work of Arts|date=2005|issue=Spring|pages=4-5|url=https://sites.ualberta.ca/~rshields/WoAReviewSpring2005.ashx|accessdate=May 1, 2018}}</ref> 3. Shields' approach is related to Henri [[Henri Lefebvre|Lefebvre]]'s social production of space.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/76898546|title=Lefebvre, love, and struggle : spatial dialectics|last=1961-|first=Shields, Rob,|date=1999|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9780415093705|location=London|oclc=76898546}}</ref> 4. Shields' interest in spatial and cultural categories led to work on [[Virtuality (philosophy)|Virtuality]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/252961315|title=The Virtual|last=Shields|first=Rob|date=2003|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=9780415281812|location=London|pages=|oclc=252961315}}</ref> in which he argued that intangibles social spatialisations were real, not abstract ideas or "socially constructed" beliefs. 5. His theory of Cultural Topologies extends spatialisation to time by considering cultural conflicts and collective memory and rhythms of places as time-space manifolds<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/868954426|title=Spatial questions : cultural topologies and social spatialisation|last=Shields|first=Rob|publisher=Sage|year=2013|isbn=9781848606654|location=London|pages=|oclc=868954426}}</ref> Shields introduces the application of topological concepts to the analysis of cultural senses of [[temporality]] as well as spatiality or [[spatialisation]]) using the example of the historical problem of the [[Seven Bridges of Königsberg|Seven Bridges of Königsburg]] solved by Leonard [[Leonhard Euler|Euler]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Shields|first1=Rob|title=Seven Bridges of Königsburg 1736|journal=Theory Culture and Society|date=2012|volume=29|issue=4-5|page=43-57|doi=10.1177/0263276412451161}}</ref> Recent work includes urban studies of walkability and pedestrians' experience of the city.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Connolly|first1=Mark|title=Edmonton pilot project targets 'pent-up demand' from pedestrians|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/edmonton-pilot-project-pedestrian-routes-walking-downtown-1.4233002|accessdate=1 May 2018|work=CBC News|publisher=CBC|date=3 August 2017}}</ref>
